  "stage": {
    "id": "architecture",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Stage 2: Inside the Transformer — Architecture Deep Dive",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "multi_head_attention",
        "title": "Multi-Head Attention: Many Perspectives at Once",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- h=8 parallel heads\n- d_k=64 per head\n- concatenate and project\n\nWith 8 heads each projecting to 64-dim subspaces, the model simultaneously learns syntactic, semantic, and positional relationships. Outputs are concatenated and linearly projected back to d_model=512.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "encoder_decoder",
        "title": "The Full Transformer: Encoder & Decoder Stacks",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- 6 encoder layers\n- 6 decoder layers with cross-attention\n- causal masking in decoder\n\nCross-attention lets each decoder position query all encoder positions freely, replacing the fixed-size hidden state of RNNs with a dynamic, direct read from the full encoded source.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "feed_forward",
        "title": "The FFN: Position-wise Processing",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- two linear layers + ReLU\n- 512→2048→512\n- same weights per position\n\nEach sublayer's FFN expands to 4× the model dimension (2048), applies ReLU, then projects back — identical weights applied independently at every position, adding per-token nonlinearity after attention.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "residual_layernorm",
        "title": "Add & Norm: Keeping Deep Networks Stable",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- residual skip connection\n- LayerNorm after addition\n- prevents gradient vanishing\n\nEvery sublayer output is added to its input before layer normalization: LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x)). This residual path lets gradients flow directly through deep 6-layer stacks without vanishing.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "masking",
        "title": "Masking: Preventing the Future from Leaking",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- causal mask sets future to -∞\n- autoregressive generation\n- ensures valid probabilities\n\nDuring training the full target sequence is fed at once, but the decoder must predict each token using only past tokens. The causal mask sets future positions to −∞ before softmax, making their attention weights effectively zero.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "Why must the decoder apply a causal mask during training? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "To save computation",
        "To prevent positions from attending to future tokens, preserving the autoregressive property",
        "To handle variable-length sequences"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "To prevent positions from attending to future tokens, preserving the autoregressive property",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
    },
